# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: html-templates-slots
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-slot] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-slot] It’s been available across browsers since January 2020.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-slot] The **`<slot>`** HTML element is a placeholder inside a Web Component that you can fill with your own markup when the component is used.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-slot] This lets you create separate DOM trees and present them together.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-slot] Slots can contain plain text, other HTML elements, or other web components.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-slot] A slot can also contain default content, which is displayed if the slot is not assigned other content when the web component is used.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-slot] This element includes the global attributes.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-slot] A *named slot* is a `<slot>` element with a `name` attribute, while an *unnamed slot* has no `name` attribute, and the name defaults to the empty string.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-slot] When a shadow root uses named slot assignment, top-level child elements of its host are rendered in slots that have a matching name in their `slot` attribute.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-slot] Slot names should be unique per shadow root: if you have two slots with the same name, all of the elements with a matching `slot` attribute are rendered in the *first* slot.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-slot] All top-level child elements that don't have a `slot` attribute are rendered in the first unnamed `<slot>` element, which is referred to as the *default slot*.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-slot] The `name` has no effect if the shadow root uses manual slot assignment.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-slot] For more information see `shadowrootslotassignment` on the `<template>` element and `Element.attachShadow()`.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-slot] This HTML shows how a number of named slots might be declared within a `<template>` element.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-slot] Note that these slots are only used as slots when the template is used inside a shadow root.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] It’s been available across browsers since November 2015.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] The **`<template>`** HTML element serves as a mechanism for holding HTML fragments, which can either be used later via JavaScript or generated immediately into shadow DOM.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] Creates a shadow root for the parent element.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] It is a declarative version of the `Element.attachShadow()` method and accepts the same enumerated values.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] Exposes the internal shadow root DOM for JavaScript (recommended for most use cases).
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] Hides the internal shadow root DOM from JavaScript.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] Sets the value of the `clonable` property of a `ShadowRoot` created using this element to `true`.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] If set, a clone of the shadow host (the parent element of this `<template>`) created with `Node.cloneNode()` or `Document.importNode()` will include a shadow root in the copy.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] Sets the `customElementRegistry` property of a `ShadowRoot` created using this element to `null`, rather than the document's custom element registry.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] This allows a scoped `CustomElementRegistry` to be attached later using `CustomElementRegistry.initialize()`.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] Sets the value of the `delegatesFocus` property of a `ShadowRoot` created using this element to `true`.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] If this is set and a non-focusable element in the shadow tree is selected, then focus is delegated to the first focusable element in the tree.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] Sets the value of the `referenceTarget` property of a `ShadowRoot` created using this element.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] The value should be the ID of an element inside the shadow DOM.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] If set, target references to the host element from outside the shadow DOM will cause the referenced target element to become the effective target of the reference to the host element.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] Sets the value of the `serializable` property of a `ShadowRoot` created using this element to `true`.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] If set, the shadow root may be serialized by calling the `Element.getHTML()` or `ShadowRoot.getHTML()` methods with the `options.serializableShadowRoots` parameter set `true`.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] Sets the `slotAssignment` property of a `ShadowRoot` created using this element.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] This is the declarative equivalent of the `slotAssignment` option of the `Element.attachShadow()` method.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] Elements are automatically assigned to `<slot>` elements within this shadow root.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] Elements with the `slot` attribute are assigned to the first `<slot>` in the template that has the corresponding `name` attribute.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] If multiple elements specify the same slot name, they are all added to the first slot in the template that has that name, and rendered in the order they are declared.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] All unnamed elements — elements that don't specify a `slot` attribute — are assigned to the default slot in the order they are declared.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] This is the first unnamed `<slot>` in the template.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] Elements are manually assigned to particular slot elements using `HTMLSlotElement.assign()`.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] This element has no permitted content, because everything nested inside it in the HTML source does not actually become the children of the `<template>` element.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] The `Node.childNodes` property of the `<template>` element is always empty, and you can only access said nested content via the special `content` property.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] However, if you call `Node.appendChild()` or similar methods on the `<template>` element, then you would be inserting children into the `<template>` element itself, which is a violation of its content model and does not actually update the `DocumentFragment` returned by the `content` property.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] Due to the way the `<template>` element is parsed, all `<html>`, `<head>`, and `<body>` opening and closing tags inside the template are syntax errors and are ignored by the parser, so `<template><head><title>Test</title></head></template>` is the same as `<template><title>Test</title></template>`.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] There are two main ways to use the `<template>` element.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] By default, the element's content is not rendered.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] The corresponding `HTMLTemplateElement` interface includes a standard `content` property (without an equivalent content/markup attribute).
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] This `content` property is read-only and holds a `DocumentFragment` that contains the DOM subtree represented by the template.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] The `Node.cloneNode()` and `Document.importNode()` methods both create a copy of a node.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] The difference is that `importNode()` clones the node in the context of the calling document, whereas `cloneNode()` uses the document of the node being cloned.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] The document context determines the `CustomElementRegistry` for constructing any custom elements.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] For this reason, use `document.importNode()` to clone the `content` fragment so that custom element descendants are constructed using the definitions in the current document, rather than the separate document that owns the template content.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] See the `Node.cloneNode()` page's examples for more details.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] Note that the `DocumentFragment` container itself should not have data attached to it.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] See the Data on the DocumentFragment is not cloned example for more details.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] If the `<template>` element contains the `shadowrootmode` attribute with a value of either `open` or `closed`, the HTML parser will immediately generate a shadow DOM.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] The element is replaced in the DOM by its content wrapped in a `ShadowRoot`, which is attached to the parent element.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] This is the declarative equivalent of calling `Element.attachShadow()` to attach a shadow root to an element.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] If the element has any other value for `shadowrootmode`, or does not have the `shadowrootmode` attribute, the parser generates a `HTMLTemplateElement`.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] Similarly, if there are multiple declarative shadow roots, only the first one is replaced by a `ShadowRoot` — subsequent instances are parsed as `HTMLTemplateElement` objects.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] Other attributes prefixed with `shadowroot` allow declarative customization of the `ShadowRoot`, such as controlling how slots are assigned.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] First we start with the HTML portion of the example.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] First, we have a table into which we will later insert content using JavaScript code.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] Then comes the template, which describes the structure of an HTML fragment representing a single table row.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] Now that the table has been created and the template defined, we use JavaScript to insert rows into the table, with each row being constructed using the template as its basis.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] In this example, a hidden support warning is included at the beginning of the markup.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] This warning is later set to be displayed via JavaScript if the browser doesn't support the `shadowrootmode` attribute.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] Next, there are two `<article>` elements, each containing nested `<style>` elements with different behaviors.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] The first `<style>` element is global to the whole document.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] The second one is scoped to the shadow root generated in place of the `<template>` element because of the presence of the `shadowrootmode` attribute.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] This example demonstrates how `shadowrootdelegatesfocus` is applied to a shadow root that is created declaratively, and the effect this has on focus.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] The code first declares a shadow root inside a `<div>` element, using the `<template>` element with the `shadowrootmode` attribute.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] This displays both a non-focusable `<div>` containing text and a focusable `<input>` element.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] It also uses CSS to style elements with `:focus` to blue, and to set the normal styling of the host element.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] The second code block is identical except that it sets the `shadowrootdelegatesfocus` attribute, which delegates focus to the first focusable element in the tree if a non-focusable element in the tree is selected.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] Last of all we use the following CSS to apply a red border to the parent `<div>` element when it has focus.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] When the HTML is first rendered, the elements have no styling, as shown in the first image.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] For the shadow root that does not have `shadowrootdelegatesfocus` set you can click anywhere except the `<input>` and the focus does not change (if you select the `<input>` element it will look like the second image).
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] For the shadow root with `shadowrootdelegatesfocus` set, clicking on the text (which is non-focusable) selects the `<input>` element, as this is the first focusable element in the tree.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] This also focuses the parent element as shown below.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] This example shows how elements can be assigned to slots in a shadow DOM based on their `slot` attribute (matched against the slot's `name` attribute).
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] First we define an `<article>` element that presents title, metadata, and article body information.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] The article contains a `<template>` element that will become a shadow root, because of the presence of the `shadowrootmode` attribute.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] We don't need to set its `shadowrootslotassignment` attribute because named slot assignment is the default.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] The template defines elements that have named slots for "header" and "meta" information, and an unnamed slot for "body" information.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] The elements are styled differently so it is easy to differentiate them.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] Inside the same host, below the template, we have four elements for populating the slots.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] The `<span>` elements have `slot` attributes that match the `name` attributes on slots in the template, and will populate the corresponding slots.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] The two `<p>` elements are unnamed, so are both inserted into the unnamed `<slot>` in the "body" element.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] The example below should show the content of the slots displayed in the appropriate sections.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] This example shows how elements can be assigned to slots in a shadow DOM using manual slot assignment.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] With this approach, each element must manually be assigned to a particular slot.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] There is no default assignment, so any slot that is not assigned will be empty.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] This warning is later set to be displayed via JavaScript if the browser doesn't support the `shadowrootslotassignment` attribute.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] Next, we define an `<article>` element that presents title, metadata, and article body information.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] This contains a `<template>` element that will become a shadow root, because of the presence of the `shadowrootmode` attribute, and will use manual slot assignment because `shadowrootslotassignment="manual"` is set.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] The template defines elements that have slots for "header", "meta", and "body" information, that can be separately referenced by their `id` attribute.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] The JavaScript for manual slot assignment is shown below.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] First the code gets the slots within the shadow root, then the text to be inserted, and finally assigns the text to the slot.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] Note that you can only assign a node once to any particular slot, and that if you assign multiple nodes to a single slot using `HTMLSlotElement.assign()`, the order they are specified controls the order they are added.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] The code displays the hidden support warning if slot assignment is not supported.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] When a `DocumentFragment` value is passed, `Node.appendChild` and similar methods move only the *child nodes* of that value into the target node.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] Therefore, it is usually preferable to attach event handlers to the children of a `DocumentFragment`, rather than to the `DocumentFragment` itself.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] Since `firstClone` is a `DocumentFragment`, only its children are added to `container` when `appendChild` is called; the event handlers of `firstClone` are not copied.
[src:html-templates-slots/elements-template] In contrast, because an event handler is added to the first *child node* of `secondClone`, the event handler is copied when `appendChild` is called, and clicking on it works as one would expect.
[src:html-templates-slots/htmlslotelement] The **`HTMLSlotElement`** interface of the Shadow DOM API enables access to the name and assigned nodes of an HTML `<slot>` element.
[src:html-templates-slots/htmlslotelement] A string used to get and set the slot's name.
[src:html-templates-slots/htmlslotelement] Sets the manually assigned nodes for this slot to the given nodes.
[src:html-templates-slots/htmlslotelement] Returns a sequence of the nodes assigned to this slot.
[src:html-templates-slots/htmlslotelement] If the `flatten` option is set to `true`, it returns a sequence of both the nodes assigned to this slot, and the nodes assigned to any other slots that are descendants of this slot.
[src:html-templates-slots/htmlslotelement] If no assigned nodes are found, it returns the slot's fallback content.
[src:html-templates-slots/htmlslotelement] Returns a sequence of the elements assigned to this slot (and no other nodes).
[src:html-templates-slots/htmlslotelement] If the `flatten` option is set to `true`, it returns a sequence of both the elements assigned to this slot, and the elements assigned to any other slots that are descendants of this slot.
[src:html-templates-slots/htmlslotelement] If no assigned elements are found, it returns the slot's fallback content.
[src:html-templates-slots/htmlslotelement] Listen to these events using `addEventListener()` or by assigning an event listener to the `oneventname` property of this interface.
[src:html-templates-slots/htmlslotelement] Fired on an `HTMLSlotElement` instance (`<slot>` element) when the node(s) contained in that slot change.
[src:html-templates-slots/htmlslotelement] The following snippet is taken from our slotchange example (see it live also).
[src:html-templates-slots/htmlslotelement] Here we grab references to all the slots, then add a slotchange event listener to the 2nd slot in the template — which is the one that keeps having its contents changed in the example.
[src:html-templates-slots/htmlslotelement] Every time the element inserted in the slot changes, we log a report to the console saying which slot has changed, and what the new node inside the slot is.
[src:html-templates-slots/htmltemplateelement] The **`HTMLTemplateElement`** interface enables access to the contents of an HTML `<template>` element.
[src:html-templates-slots/htmltemplateelement] A read-only `DocumentFragment` which contains the DOM subtree representing the `<template>` element's template contents.
[src:html-templates-slots/htmltemplateelement] A string that reflects the value of the `shadowrootmode` attribute of the associated `<template>` element.
[src:html-templates-slots/htmltemplateelement] A boolean that reflects the value of the `shadowrootdelegatesfocus` attribute of the associated `<template>` element.
[src:html-templates-slots/htmltemplateelement] A boolean that reflects the value of the `shadowrootclonable` attribute of the associated `<template>` element.
[src:html-templates-slots/htmltemplateelement] A string that reflects the value of the `shadowrootcustomelementregistry` attribute of the associated `<template>` element, indicating that the declarative shadow root will use a scoped `CustomElementRegistry`.
[src:html-templates-slots/htmltemplateelement] A boolean that reflects the value of the `shadowrootserializable` attribute of the associated `<template>` element.
[src:html-templates-slots/htmltemplateelement] A string that reflects the value of the `shadowrootslotassignment` attribute of the associated `<template>` element.
[src:html-templates-slots/template-word-processing] Once the template is completed, the user can edit, save and manage the result as an ordinary word processing document.
[src:html-templates-slots/template-word-processing] Word processing templates enable the ability to bypass the initial setup and configuration time necessary to create standardized documents such as a resume.
[src:html-templates-slots/template-word-processing] They also enable the automatic configuration of the user interface of the word processing software, with features such as autocompletion, toolbars, thesaurus, and spelling options.
[src:html-templates-slots/template-word-processing] Word processing templates are ordinarily included as a regular feature in most word processing software.
[src:html-templates-slots/template-word-processing] In addition, users of such software often have the option to create and save their own templates, to acquire them from the original vendor of the software, or from third parties.
[src:html-templates-slots/template-word-processing] Word processing templates have the standard "fill-in-the-blank" features similar to other kinds of templates in computer software.
[src:html-templates-slots/template-word-processing] They also have features that specifically leverage the functionality of the word processor user interface.
[src:html-templates-slots/template-word-processing] Additionally, support may exist for other native features unique to the word processing application.
[src:html-templates-slots/template-word-processing] Word processing document creation may ordinarily (although not necessarily) begin with selecting a template with a menu command such as: `File > New > Templates` (and select the template you wish to use), where the user is given the option of selecting a pre-existing template.
[src:html-templates-slots/template-word-processing] Similar commands are provided for creating and editing templates.
[src:html-templates-slots/template-word-processing] Template files may restrict users from saving changes with the original file name, such as with the case of Microsoft Office (.dot) filename extensions.
[src:html-templates-slots/template-word-processing] In those cases, users are prompted to save the file with a new name as if it were a new file.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] This article explains how you can use the `<template>` and `<slot>` elements to create a flexible template that can then be used to populate the shadow DOM of a web component.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] When you have to reuse the same markup structures repeatedly on a web page, it makes sense to use some kind of a template rather than repeating the same structure over and over again.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] This was possible before, but it is made a lot easier by the HTML `<template>` element.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] This element and its contents are not rendered in the DOM, but it can still be referenced using JavaScript.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] Although trivial, you can already start to see how this could be useful.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] Templates are useful on their own, but they work even better with web components.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] Let's define a web component that uses our template as the content of its shadow DOM.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] The key point to note here is that we append a clone of the template content to the shadow root, created using the `Document.importNode()` method.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] And because we are appending its contents to a shadow DOM, we can include some styling information inside the template in a `<style>` element, which is then encapsulated inside the custom element.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] This wouldn't work if we just appended it to the standard DOM.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] So far so good, but the element isn't very flexible.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] We can only display one bit of text inside it, meaning that at the moment it is even less useful than a regular paragraph!
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] We can make it possible to display different text in each element instance in a nice declarative way using the `<slot>` element.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] Slots are identified by their `name` attribute, and allow you to define placeholders in your template that can be filled with any markup fragment you want when the element is used in the markup.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] If the slot's content isn't defined when the element is included in the markup, or if the browser doesn't support slots, `<my-paragraph>` just contains the fallback content "My default text".
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] To define the slot's content, we include an HTML structure inside the `<my-paragraph>` element with a `slot` attribute whose value is equal to the name of the slot we want it to fill.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] If you want to play with it some more, you can find it on GitHub (see it running live also).
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] The `name` attribute should be unique per shadow root: if you have two slots with the same name, all of the elements with a matching `slot` attribute will be assigned to the first slot with that name.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] But the `slot` attribute does not need to be unique: a `<slot>` can be filled by multiple elements that all have a matching `slot` attribute.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] The `name` and `slot` attributes both default to the empty string, so elements with no `slot` attributes are assigned to the `<slot>` with no `name` attribute (the unnamed slot, or default slot).
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] The previous example uses *named slot assignment*, which means the named `<slot>` elements in a template are populated with the content of elements in the custom component (or more generally the host element) that have matching names in their `slot` attributes.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] This is the original mechanism used for slot assignment and is the most suitable method for most use cases.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] Manual assignment is useful when you want to dynamically select the content to be slotted, or if you want to assign slots based on some other element attribute such as their `id`, without having to add duplicate `slot` attributes.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] For example, a `<movie-picker>` custom element might use a `<select>` element to filter on genre, slotting only the elements that have a matching `data-genre` attribute value on change.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] Named slot assignment is the default behavior.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] On user agents that support setting the shadow root slot assignment method, you can enable this feature when you attach the shadow root.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] This is done programmatically using the `options.slotAssignment` parameter passed to `Element.attachShadow()`, or declaratively by setting the `shadowrootslotassignment` attribute on the `<template>` element.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] The following HTML shows a basic example of how you can set `shadowrootslotassignment` when declaratively creating a shadow root (using `shadowrootmode`).
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] To finish off the article, let's look at something a little less trivial.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] However, it is generally more practical to add slots within a `<template>` element, since you are unlikely to need to define a pattern based on an already-rendered element.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] In addition, even if it is not already rendered, the purpose of the container as a template should be more semantically clear when using the `<template>`.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] In addition, `<template>` can have items directly added to it, like `<td>`, which would disappear when added to a `<div>`.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] Next, let's create a new custom element named **`<element-details>`** and use `Element.attachShadow` to attach to it, as its shadow root, that document fragment we created with our `<template>` element above.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] This uses exactly the same pattern as we saw in our earlier trivial example.
[src:html-templates-slots/using-templates-and-slots] Finally let's put all the snippets together and see what the rendered result looks like.
